Scripts

This page is the heart of my current work. It shows the basic steps of how I select a model for my data to correlate duration and species traits, and later on apply this model on extant species to compare modelled extinction risk and extinction risk estimated by the IUCN Red List assassment

Data

I am currently using a dataset which is different from the one which is going to be published in the end. Please note therefore that the attributes of the dataset, for example the distribution of numerical variables and alike, are very similar to the original dataset, but this is not real data right now. This is just a simple precaution due to the fact that it took me quite some time to collect this data, so I don`t want to give it away before publishing it. The data has mostly numerical variables like coordinates or also geogrpahic ranges, but also information about habitats and body size. For a full description of variables used, see the script below.

The script

In the following you find the RMarkdown file produced by my current modelling trials. This is the same file you can download and try yourself by following the link provided above to GitHub. All you need is a running R installation. I am happy to receive any kinds of feedback on my work!

Data explanation

Variable definitions:

variable name details
species the binomial species name
order the taxonomic order of the species
ma_range duration the species covered in the fossil record in million years
mni_max minimum number of individuals in one location, maximum value for each species
spec_max maximum number of specimens in one location, maximum value for each species
grid_cells number of grid cells a species occupies
gcd maximum great circle distance; shortest connection between two points on the surface of a sphere
lat_range maximum latitudinal range of a species (maximum difference between paleolatitudes)
mean_lat mean latitude calculated from all species occurrences
min_lat minimum latitude
hab.cat.b habitat category; low, high, or highlow (last one meaning both). Distinguished basically between flowing and stagnant water bodies
habitat_width number of habitats utilized by the species (1 to 4)
bodysize maximum or only available skull length; values scaled from 0 to 1
noo total number of occurrences per species

First notes

  • Mean latitude and minimum latitude are strongly correlated, one of them probably has to be removed from the model
  • Grid cells, GCD and latitudinal range are correlated
  • Geo distribution and habitat width seem positively correlated (makes sense)
  • Grid cells increase correlates with duration(ok with IUCN)
  • Body size increase decreases duration (bigger=worse, ok with IUCN)
  • Body size seems bigger in small habitat widths (singelton bias?) OK (2)
  • Body size increase decreases geo ranges? OK (2)
  • More habitats increase duration (see boxplot) OK (1)
  • Min + mean latitude increase with habitat width (northern hemisphere seems to have larger habitat widths) OK (3)
  • Lat range, GDC and grid cells seem larger in northern hemisphere OK (3)

Body size and geo range follow patterns we observe today as well. Abundance seems to be a difficult pattern. Things to check in more detail will be why there is larger habitat widths and also ranges in the northern hemisphere, and why big species should occupy only one habitat type. Main emphasis will be to check if these patterns are likely caused by sampling/preservation bias.

Yes the median durations between habitat width groups (1,2,3) differ significantly, although category 4 just has one single count and therefore cannot be used. If removing all singe-interval species this pattern is still roughly visible but not significant any longer.
There is a positive correlation (apparently non monotonous as stronger using spearmans) between number of occurrences and number of habitat types. This seems natural,as the number of habitats is required as minimum number of occurrences for each habitat width. However, regarding preservation probability the number of occurrences simply could be the reason for the observed pattern between duration and habitat width as it potentially influences both duration and habitat width.

Correcting for number of occurrences in each species does however not seem justified as this would rule out the possibility of species just being more abundant as well as excessively punishing very abundant species (e.g. Opisthotriton kayi with 71 occurrences in 3 habitat types.).

Are differences caused by larger sample size in the northern hemisphere?

stat <- c()
p.stat <- c()
south <- dat[dat$mean_lat<0,]
north <- dat[dat$mean_lat>=0,]
for(i in 1:1000){
  temp.n <- north[sample(c(1:nrow(north)), nrow(south)),]
  temp <- rbind(temp.n, south)
  res <- cor.test(temp$mean_lat, temp$habitat_width, method="spearman")
  stat <- c(stat, res$estimate[[1]])
  p.stat <- c(p.stat, res$p.value[[1]])
  i <- i+1
}

Repeated subsampling without replacement of northern hemisphere occurrences by the number of the southern hemisphere occurrences gives a median correlation between mean latitude and habitat width of 0.1759072 (mad=0.037887 ), with 0.866 being significantly correlated. As the correlation lies well within 2mads of the distribution, the influence of the more intense sampling of the northern hemisphere on the correlation between mean latitude and habitat width can be neglected.

0.8916667 % of residuals are within a range of +- 2 million years, thats awesome (too good?) given the average stage length is longer.
Also: there might be some deviation from constant variance assumption (residuals~fitted values), there seem to be 3 outliers in the data (normal-q-q plot: 9,61, 146). Residuals are getting larger with values getting larger, with one clear outlier. ### Mulitcolinearity min_lat and mean_lat are strongly correlated, so assumptions are violated here. According to wikipedia, Multicollinearity does not reduce the predictive power or reliability of the model as a whole, at least within the sample data set; it only affects calculations regarding individual predictors. That is, a multiple regression model with correlated predictors can indicate how well the entire bundle of predictors predicts the outcome variable, but it may not give valid results about any individual predictor, or about which predictors are redundant with respect to others. This is especially strange as removing one of the correlated variables results in a stark drop of R squared. For colinerarity, correlation needs to be linear. Coefficients change not dramatically when removing one of the variables, but testing the insignificant variables from the multilinear model alone shows significant effects in simple linear regression for noo and habitat_width. I will keep both variables for now.

Removing outliers makes a big difference, however all these outliers are species that actually have long durations. In a model with lots of short and just few long durations, this could be falsely identified as outlier. Excluding is likely not the best thing to do here.

Logtransforming the data increases adjusted R squared.
Cross validation of the linear model with logged response variable shows that high values are constantly underpredicted, while small values tend to get overpredicted. However, the trend within the predictions is right: Large values are mostly predicted larger values by the model than small values. Cross validated standard error of estimate is 4.127 million years in this model.

Conclusion

The linear model explains around 30% of the observed data, however it suffers from multicolinearity between mean and minimum latitude. This makes estimates for predictor coeffiecients less precise and potentially roduces type 2 errors. Removing one of these factors however reduces explained variance dramatically. Logging the dependent variable seems appropriate, given that the outcome variable is highly skewed.

Generalized linear model (GLM)

The generalized linear model uses a poisson distribution as a proxy for a negative binomial function.

# pseudo r^2
R2logit<- function(model){
    R2<- 1-(model$deviance/model$null.deviance)
    return(R2)
}

Generalized linear mixed model (GLMM)

My fixed effects are the range and abundance, my random effects (grouping variable) are the orders the data comes from. I am using a negative binomial distribution again.

Generalized additive model (GAM)

Use mgcv, not gam package, as this supports neg binomial.

#library(gam)
library(mgcv)
gam.all <- gam(data=dat.m, ma_range ~ s(mni_max) + grid_cells + s(bodysize) + s(lat_range) + s(mean_lat) + s(min_lat)+
               hab.cat.b)
summary(gam.all)
hist(gam.all$residuals, breaks=40)

gam.negbin <- gam(data=dat.m, ma_range ~ s(mni_max) + grid_cells + s(bodysize) + s(lat_range) + s(mean_lat) + s(min_lat)+
               hab.cat.b, family=negbin(2)) #
summary(gam.negbin)
hist(gam.negbin$residuals, breaks=40)

Model looks good, explains almost 90% of the data, so probably overfitted. Using negative binomial family overfits the model enourmously and produces negative R^2! This gets worse the smaller theta is chosen. Negbin is the wrong family.

Zero-Inflated model

Worth a try as the data includes lots of zeros, some of them might be produced by preservation bias instead of being real.

library(pscl)
## Classes and Methods for R developed in the
## Political Science Computational Laboratory
## Department of Political Science
## Stanford University
## Simon Jackman

f1 <- formula(as.integer(ma_range)~ mni_max + grid_cells + bodysize + lat_range + mean_lat + min_lat) # + hab.cat.b
zi1 <- zeroinfl(f1, dist="negbin", link="logit", data=dat.m)

Generalized boosted model

This is a machine learning technique. Models are quite immune to overfitting and can also deal with correlations of variables. Sounds promising! GBM also handles missing data, not sure yet what this means in detail though.

library(gbm)
gbm.all <- gbm(data=dat, as.integer(ma_range)~ mni_max + grid_cells + gcd + bodysize + lat_range + mean_lat + min_lat
               + factor(hab.cat.b),
               n.trees=1000, distribution = "poisson",
               cv.folds = 3)
summary(gbm.all, las=2)
hist(dat$ma_range-gbm.all$fit, breaks=40) # residuals

gbm.sub <- gbm(data=dat.m, as.integer(ma_range)~ mni_max + gcd + grid_cells + bodysize + lat_range + mean_lat + min_lat
               + factor(hab.cat.b),
               n.trees=1000, distribution = "poisson")
summary(gbm.sub, las=2)
hist(dat.m$ma_range-gbm.sub$fit, breaks=40) # residuals

# comparing complete data versus incomplete data
all <- summary(gbm.all)
sub <- summary(gbm.sub)
comp <- merge(all, sub, by="var")
plot(comp[,2]~comp[,3], col="grey", ylab="incomplete data", xlab="complete data", pch=3)
text(comp[,3], comp[,2], labels=comp$var)

# Plots the marginal effect of the selected variables by "integrating" out the other variables.
#plot.gbm(gbm.all, i.var=c(1)) # 
#plot.gbm(gbm.all, i.var=c(4,5))

The models based on all data and complete cases only differ strongly.
